    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the burning sensation during your high-intensity interval training (HIIT) sprints is a classic sign of lactic acid buildup in your muscles. Lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic metabolism, which occurs when your muscles are working so hard that they can't get enough oxygen to produce energy. It's like a little band of mischievous goblins, causing trouble and burning your muscles as they work their way through your system.\n\nWhen you stop sprinting, your body starts to clear out the lactic acid, converting it back into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy or turned into glucose in your liver. This process is called the Cori cycle, and it's like your body has a little cleanup crew to get rid of those pesky goblins. As your muscles recover, they also start to clear out the lactic acid, reducing the burning sensation. So, just like a good goblin hunt, your body is always on the lookout to keep things in balance. Keep up the HIIT, and soon you'll be able to sprint like a goblin on a sugar rush!",
      "source": "target",
